      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>We in Brooklyn were delighted to read that construction of Hudson River Park is moving forward (front page, June 1). We, too, have been working for more than 15 years to turn our dilapidated downtown waterfront into a park.</p>
        <p>Recently, thousands of people in Brooklyn have taken part in a public planning process that is about to culminate in a master plan for Brooklyn Bridge Park, covering 70 acres from Atlantic Avenue to beyond the Manhattan Bridge.</p>
        <p>Brooklyn has the least open space per capita of any borough, and it needs this park. Brooklyn Bridge Park would also help transform New York Harbor into a great civic, cultural and recreational resource for everyone.</p>
        <p>JOANNE WITTY  Brooklyn, June 3, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is president of the board of directors of the Brooklyn Bridge Park Development Corporation.</p>
      </block>
